:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE006434%2F1"><gtr:id>F33FFEB8-0F05-485A-B233-F94EC39A1766</gtr:id><gtr:title>What Do Others' Nonverbal Expressions Tell Us? - The Social Appraisal of Emotion</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E006434/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The first goal of this project is to disseminate the results of previous doctoral research of the first author through publications and conference presentations. Second, relevant methodological and teaching-related training and the submission of research grant applications will prepare future career development. Finally, the results of new empirical studies will consolidate and extend previous research on the social appraisal of emotions. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Two laboratory experiments will use reaction time measures to examine whether there is an automatic influence of others? nonverbal emotional behaviour on people?s perceptions and evaluations of an emotional situation. Participants will be briefly exposed to pictures of emotional facial expressions. After each exposure, they will need to quickly judge pre-tested words and it will be examined whether the type of emotion observed earlier has an effect on the speed and accuracy of this judgement. This will allow inferences about the meanings that people rapidly extract from others' faces. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>A second study will reanalyse previously collected videotapes of participants in emotional situations to identify the micro-momentary facial signals that communicate situational evaluations. A final questionnaire study amongst teachers will examine whether such processes are possibly relevant to bullying behaviour in a school setting. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>68833</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>AE337E16-EBBA-4D0E-883B-972BF5C0C98E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Emotional signals in nonverbal interaction: dyadic facilitation and convergence in expressions, appraisals, and feelings.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cognition &amp; emotion</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/f0163c5ef7cf955335837a20cc99f7be"><gtr:id>f0163c5ef7cf955335837a20cc99f7be</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bruder M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0269-9931</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>546fb9e2297e99.83701473</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F13D6D46-6E76-4B43-977A-638BB23E8EAD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Regulating emotion in the context of interpersonal decisions: the role of anticipated pride and regret.</gtr:title